'''Christina Maranci''' (born 1968) is an American researcher, writer, translator, historian, and Professor at [[Tufts University]]. She is considered an expert on the history and development of [[Armenian architecture]].<ref name=Spanish>{{cite web|title=Christina Maranci|url=http://www.genocidioarmenio.org/christina-maranci/|publisher=Genocidio Armenio|accessdate=22 February 2013|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=maranci12>{{cite news|title=U.S. prof. calls to save Mren Cathedral of Western Armenia|url=http://www.panarmenian.net/eng/news/147243/US_prof_calls_to_save_Mren_Cathedral_of_Western_Armenia|accessdate=25 February 2013|newspaper=PanArmenian|date=February 23, 2013|quote=Prof. Maranci’s areas of expertise include Byzantine art and architecture, and the art and architecture of the Transcaucasus - principally Armenia.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Turkey restores Armenian church to show goodwill|url=http://today.az/news/politics/38272.html|accessdate=22 February 2013|newspaper=The International Herald Tribune|date=March 23, 2007|quote=Christina Maranci, an expert on medieval Armenian architecture at the University of Wisconsin in Milwaukee}}</ref>
==Life== Of [[Armenians|Armenian]] descent, Maranci's father was born in [[Istanbul]], [[Turkey]]. Maranci was born in 1968 in the United States. She attained her Bachelor of Arts degree in Art History at the [[Vassar College]] in 1990. She continued her education and received a master's degree at the [[Princeton University]] in the Art and Archeology department.<ref name=Tufts>{{cite web|title=CHRISTINA MARANCI|url=http://ase.tufts.edu/art/documents/cvs/maranci.pdf|work=Department of Art History|publisher=Tufts University|accessdate=20 February 2013}}</ref> She received her Ph.D. at [[Princeton University]] in the Art and Archeology department with her dissertation, ''Medieval Armenian Architecture in Historiography: Josef Strzygowski and his Legacy''.<ref name=Tufts1>{{cite web|title="Rock, Paper, Scissors: The Excavation and Reconstruction of Zvartnots" A Talk by Dr. Christina Maranci, Arthur H. Dadian and Ara Oztemel Chair of Armenian Art and Architecture at Tufts University.|url=http://www.almainc.org/calendar_events_zvartnots.html|publisher=Armenian Library and Museum of America|accessdate=22 February 2013}}</ref> She was an Assistant Professor at the [[University of Wisconsin&ndash;Milwaukee]] from 2001 to 2004, and an Associate Professor there through 2008. She is currently a professor of the Department of Art and Art History at the [[Tufts University]]. She teaches many courses in Byzantine and Armenian architecture such as Byzantine Art and Architecture, Introduction to the Arts of Armenia, and The Art of War: Building Churches in Early Medieval Armenia.<ref name=Tufts />
==Notable fellowship and awards== *Calouste Gulbenkian Foundation Fellowship (1995-7)<ref name=Peeters>{{cite web|title=Medieval Armenian Architecture Constructions of Race and Nation|url=http://www.peeters-leuven.be/boekoverz_print.asp?nr=7150|publisher=Peeters Publishers|accessdate=5 March 2013}}</ref> *Mellon Dissertation Research Fellowship, Princeton University (1997-8)<ref name=Peeters /> *University of Madison, Wisconsin - Graduate School Research Award Fellowship (2006){{Citation needed|date=March 2013}} *University of Madison, Wisconsin - Center for 21st-Century Studies Research Fellowship (2007-8){{Citation needed|date=March 2013}} *Tufts University - Faculty and Research Award (2010){{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}
She is featured in the 2011 book ''Encyclopedia of Prominent Armenian Women'' edited by [[Zori Balayan]].<ref name=Tufts /><ref>{{cite book|last=Balayan|first=Zori|title=Hayuhiner: Hanragitaran erku hatorov|year=2011|publisher=Amaras|location=Yerevan|accessdate=22 February 2013|language=Armenian|quote=Title translated from Armenian: "Encyclopedia of Prominent Armenian Women"}}</ref>
==Works== Maranci's research is mainly on [[medieval Armenia]]n history and the relationship with the Sasanian, Byzantine, and Islamic empires.<ref name=mazda /> She also focuses on the problems found in modern historigraphy.<ref name=mazda>{{cite book|last=Hovannisian|first=ed. by Richard G.|title=Armenian Sebastia/Sivas and Lesser Armenia|year=2004|publisher=Mazda Publ.|location=Costa Mesa, Calif.|isbn=1568591527}}</ref> Maranci's book ''Medieval Armenian Architecture: Constructions of Race and Nation'', highlights art historian [[Josef Strzygowski]] and his important contributions and influence in the studies of [[Armenian architecture]].<ref name=mazda /> Her recent works focus on the Byzantine influence into Armenian art and architecture.<ref name=mazda /> She has published ''A Survival Guide for Art History Students'' which provides Art History students with helpful assistance and information to help them when taking Art History courses.<ref>{{cite book|last=Maranci|first=Christina|title=A survival guide for art history students|year=2005|publisher=Pearson/Prentice Hall|location=Upper Saddle River, NJ|isbn=0131401971}}</ref> The languages Christina Maranci researches in include Italian, English, German, French, Armenian ([[Grabar|Classical Armenian]] and [[Ashkharhabar|Modern Armenian]]) and Greek.<ref name=Tufts />
Maranci is also deemed as one of the world's experts and authorities on the [[Cathedral of Mren]], an Armenian cathedral in Turkey that is on the verge of collapse.<ref name=maranci12 /><ref name=Mren>{{cite news|title=A Cathedral on the Verge of Collapse: The Campaign to Save Mren|url=http://massispost.com/archives/8056|accessdate=22 February 2013|newspaper=Massis}}</ref>
===Books=== *''Medieval Armenian Architecture: Constructions of Race and Nation'' (2001) *''A Survival Guide for Art History Students'' (2004) *''Vigilant Powers: Three Churches of Early Medieval Armenia'' (2015) *''The Art of Armenia: An Introduction'' (2018)
