The '''Dialogue on Translation between a Lord and a Clerk''' forms the preface of [[John Trevisa]]'s 1387 translation of the ''[[Polychronicon]]'' of [[Ranulf Higden]], made for his patron, [[Thomas de Berkeley, 5th Baron Berkeley|Lord Berkeley]]. Written in [[Middle English]], it consists of a series of arguments made by the clerk (representing Trevisa) on why books should not be translated from learned languages such as [[Latin]], each one followed by a rebuttal from the Lord (representing Lord Berkeley). The clerk eventually agrees and the dialogue concludes with a prayer for guidance in the translation.

