{{Infobox journal | cover = [[Image:IJALcover.gif]] | discipline = [[Linguistics]] | abbreviation = Int. J. Am. Linguist. | publisher = [[University of Chicago Press]] | country = US | history = 1917-present | frequency = Quarterly | impact = .18 | impact-year = 2012 | website = http://www.journals.uchicago.edu/ijal | ISSN = 0020-7071 }}
The '''''International Journal of American Linguistics''''' (''IJAL'') is an [[academic journal]] devoted to the study of the [[indigenous languages of the Americas]]. It was established in 1917 by anthropologist [[Franz Boas]]; it has been published by the [[University of Chicago Press]] since 1974.<ref>{{Cite journal| issn = 0020-7071| volume = 39| issue = 4| pages = 275| title = Back Matter| journal = International Journal of American Linguistics| date = 1973-10-01| jstor = 1264837}}</ref> ''IJAL'' focuses on the investigation of linguistic data and the presentation of grammatical fragments and other documents relevant to Amerindian languages.
